09225nam a22011895i 9783110920833DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20122005gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013949682  a97831109208337 a10.1515/97831109208332doi  a(DE-B1597)56633  a(OCoLC)840445173  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aP290b.M67 2005 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a415/.9222  aET 6502rvk0(DE-625)rvk/28012:00aMorphosyntactic Expression in Functional Grammar /ced. by Casper de Groot, Kees Hengeveld. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2012] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (534 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aFunctional Grammar Series [FGS] ,x0926-5147 ;v2700ti-iv -- tPreface -- tContents -- tAgreement: More arguments for the dynamic expression model -- tConstituent ordering in the expression component of Functional Grammar -- tDynamic expression in Functional Discourse Grammar -- tNoun incorporation in Functional Discourse Grammar -- tMorphosyntactic templates -- tA crosslinguistic study of ‘locative inversion’: Evidence for the Functional Discourse Grammar model -- tThe agreement cross-reference continuum: Person marking in FG -- tThe explanatory power of typological hierarchies: Developmental perspectives on non-verbal predication -- tNon-verbal predicability and copula support rule in Spanish Sign Language -- tA new view on the semantics and pragmatics of operators of aspect, tense and quantification -- tExclamation: Sentence type, illocution or modality? -- tClose appositions -- tInversion and the absence of grammatical relations in Plains Cree -- tDirection diathesis and obviation in Functional Grammar: The case of the inverse in Mapudungun, an indigenous language of south central Chile -- tUnexpected insertion or omission of an absolutive marker as an icon of a surprising turn of events in discourse -- tPronominal expression rule ordering in Danish and the question of a discourse grammar -- tIndex of names -- tIndex of languages -- tIndex of subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMorphological and syntactic issues have received relatively little attention in Functional Grammar, due to the fact that this grammatical model, given its functional orientation, was primarily concerned with developing its pragmatic and semantic components. Now that these have been solidly developed, this book turns to the further development of the syntactic and morphological components of the model. Two recent developments receive pride of place: Bakker's Dynamic Expression Model and Hengeveld and Mackenzie's Functional Discourse Grammar. The first model aims at accounting for the complex interactions that one finds in many languages between the sets of expression rules that have to account for form on the one hand and those that establish order on the other. The second model takes a further step by considering morphosyntactic and phonological representations to be part of the underlying structure of the grammar rather than as the output of that grammar, contrary to the original assumptions in FG. The book accordingly contains synopses of these two proposals as well as applications of these to a variety of linguistic phenomena. Further articles provide detailed analyses of a range of semantic and pragmatic categories and their morphosyntactic expression in a wide variety of languages. The articles in this book contain data on some 60 different languages, including focused articles on phenomena in Arabic, Danish, English, Lengua de Señas Española, Mapudungun, Plains Cree, and Tanggu. In all, the contributions to this volume show that the issue of morphosyntactic expression in Functional Grammar is very much alive and moving into promising new directions, while at the same time contributing to a better understanding of a large number of morphosyntactic phenomena in a wide variety of languages.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aFunctionalism (Linguistics). 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxMorphosyntax. 4aFunktionalismus (Linguistik). 4aMorphologie. 4aSyntax. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aFunctionalism (linguistics).  aMorphology.  asyntax.1 aBakker, Dik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoland, Annerieke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConnolly, John H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCornish, Francis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGroot, Casper de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGroot, Casper de, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHengeveld, Kees, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHengeveld, Kees, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHerrero-Blanco, Ángel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJakobsen, Lisbeth Falster, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeizer, Evelien, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLotterman, Johan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMackenzie, J. Lachlan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoutaouakil, Ahmed, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSalazar-García, Ventura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSiewierska, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmit, Niels, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThomsen, Ole Neder